File MonthlyCurrencyData.csv contains the monthly exchange rate of USD/JPY and USD/CNY for the same time period. Similarly to homework 2, we will aggregate the daily data into weekly data. We will compare our analysis using ARMA modeling on both weekly and monthly data for the two currencies.

Question 1. Weekly vs Monthly Exploratory Data Analysis (20 points)

1a. Based on your intuition, when would you use weekly instead of monthly time series data?

Response

We can think of the difference between the monthly and the daily datasets to be a factor of math. The monthly set would be an average of the daily sets for that month. As such, we would expect to see much less volatility in the monthly set, and a less drastic jump from data points. However, this average, or smoothing, of data into a monthly set would inherently remove any intelligence gleaned from the analysis of outliers present in the daily dataset. I would expect as is the monthly data is smoothed, it inherently may exhibit more stationarity when compared to the daily dataset. Given the power of the current analytic tools, I expect equal trends of the data to emerge in a linear trend, however higher order model would lack the nuance when deployed on the monthly dataset. As for seasonality, there is a chance that there is seasonality within the month, and and this is hidden but the averaging. seasonality outside the period of a single month should emerge in both datasets.

Response: Weekly vs Monthly Time Series data comparison

In comparing the weekly vs monthly plot of both currencies, we see that the data mirrors each other, and follows the same overall path. We see less datapoints and less viotility in the weekly dataset, but all macrotrends are captured.

In comparing the straight plots of the time series of each currancy, We see that issue of scale is apparent. because of the magnitude of the JPY conversion rate against the USD, when compared to the CNY, the CNY plots as a relatively straight line, as the different between the min and max values within the CNY dataset is significantly smaller than that of JPY.

In order to get around this issue of magnitude, we normalized the JPY data such that the real exchange rate was multiplied by the ratio of average CNY to average JPY. This allowed for the JPY to effectively be scaled into the CNY values range, and when plotted, shows the difference in the movement of the two currency exchange rates. We can see that even in this normalized plot, the range and variance of JPY is larger and more dynamic than compared with that of CNY.

Looking at the acf plots, we see that the CNY exihibits more stationarity when compared with JPY although a significant amount of the plot is outside the significance line, indicating that both are non-stationary. This makes sense, given that there are a vast number of political, economic and intangiable variables that impact the exchange rate. We are not suprised that the CNY shows less variance, given the strong coupling of these items between CNY and USD, in comparison with JPY and USD.

Response: Comparing Trend Estimation using weekly vs Monthly Data

In looking at CNY, we can see that as the month is just the average of the week, the resulting model and acf is really an average as well. we see that the weekly plot of CNY model has more nuanced variance, better fitting the model, likely because of the nuance in the weekly measure, vs the monthly measure. We see that after the lag of 8, it is stationary. For the JPY plot, we see almost exactly the same results, with the lag = 10 the start of stationarity.

In looking at both currencies, we see that the model reasonably follows the data, with the weekly model being better as it captures the nuances of the inter-week variations within a month. The JPY has a large magnitude of max, min and mean, and thus the variance is greater. Both model show a stationarity after a period of lag, with CNY has a steeper trend towards stationarity.

Response: Exploratory Analysis of 1st Order Difference Data

How do the difference time series for the two currencies compare in terms of serial dependence and stationarity

Comparing the monthly and weekly data for each, we see that the Monthly significance bands are wider than that of the weekly. This makes sense, since the monthly data points are farther away if the grouping of 4 weeks average is further from the previous, whereas for weeks, the there is less distance between consecutive points. These wider bands also then ensure that more of the ACF is within the significance bands, although both are generally stationary.

In comparing the currencies, we see that the JPY differencing results in a more stationary and smoother plot, in compared to that of CNY. Again, this is because of the wider absolute differences, when compared to CNY. We also see more serial dependence on JPY, with smaller jumps between data points.

Question 2. ARIMA Fitting and Forecasting: Weekly Data Analysis (23 points)

2a. Divide the data into training and testing data set, where the training data exclude the last eight weeks of data (November and December 2021) with the testing data including the last eight weeks of data. For both currency exchange rates and using the training datasets, use the iterative model to fit an ARIMA(p,d,q) model with max AR and MA orders of 8, and a differencing order of 1 or 2. Display the summary of the final model fit. Compare statistical significance of the coefficients. Would a lower order model be suggested based on the statistical significance of the coefficients?

Analyzing weekly data with ARIMA model fitting

#p value function
pvalue.coef <- function(tv) {  2 * (1 - pnorm(abs(tv)))}


weekly.CNY.ts.train = weekly.CNY.ts[0:618]
weekly.CNY.ts.test = weekly.CNY.ts[619:626]
weekly.JPY.ts.train = weekly.JPY.ts[0:618]
weekly.JPY.ts.test = weekly.JPY.ts[619:626]


###### Fit an AR(p) process for for p<= order.max ####
TimeSeriesData = weekly.CNY.ts.train
orderMax = 8

mod = ar(weekly.CNY.ts.train,order.max=orderMax)

# What is the selected order?

mod$order
## [1] 5
# find the list of arguments provided by AR fit
summary(mod)
##              Length Class  Mode     
## order          1    -none- numeric  
## ar             5    -none- numeric  
## var.pred       1    -none- numeric  
## x.mean         1    -none- numeric  
## aic            9    -none- numeric  
## n.used         1    -none- numeric  
## n.obs          1    -none- numeric  
## order.max      1    -none- numeric  
## partialacf     8    -none- numeric  
## resid        618    -none- numeric  
## method         1    -none- character
## series         1    -none- character
## frequency      1    -none- numeric  
## call           3    -none- call     
## asy.var.coef  25    -none- numeric
# plot aic values
# On non-log scale it is difficult to detect the minimum.
plot(c(0:orderMax),mod$aic+.0001, type="b",log="y",xlab="order",ylab="log-AIC CNY values", col="red")

# Are the roots of fitted AR within the unit circle?
# extract roots from the model output
roots = polyroot(c(1,(-mod$ar)))
# adjust the x and y -axis limits to include the full circle
plot(roots,xlim=c(-1.5,1.5),ylim=c(-1.5,1.5), col="red")
# draw a unit root circle
lines(complex(arg = seq(0,2*pi,len=300)))

# residuals analysis
resids = mod$resid[(mod$order+1): length(mod$resid)]

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(resids,xlab="",ylab="Model Residuals", col="red")
acf(resids,main='ACF of the Model Residuals', col="red")
pacf(resids,main='PACF of the Model Residuals', col="red")
qqnorm(resids, col="red")

###### Fit an ARMA(p,q) for some values of p and q #####
modarma = arima(TimeSeriesData, order = c(8,0,8),method = "ML")

par (mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(resid(modarma), ylab='Standardized Residuals', col="red")
abline(h=0)
acf(as.vector(resid(modarma)),main= 'ACF of the Model Residuals', col="red")
pacf(as.vector(resid(modarma)),main='PACF of the Model Residuals', col="red")
qqnorm(resid(modarma), col="red")
qqline(resid(modarma), col="red")

## Order selection -- AIC 
n = length(TimeSeriesData)
norder = 4
p = c(1:norder)-1; q = c(1:norder)-1; d = c(1:1)-1
aic = matrix(0,norder,norder,)
for(i in 1:norder){
   for(j in 1:norder){
    modij = arima(TimeSeriesData,order = c(p[i],0,q[j]), method='ML')
    aic[i,j] = modij$aic-2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)+2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)*n/(n-p[i]-q[j]-2)
   }  
 }

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
#which order to select?
aicv = as.vector(aic)  
plot(aicv,ylab="AIC values", col="red")

indexp = rep(c(1:norder),norder)
indexq = rep(c(1:norder),each=norder)
indexaic = which(aicv == min(aicv))
porder = indexp[indexaic]-1
qorder = indexq[indexaic]-1


porder
## [1] 3
qorder
## [1] 3
#Create Final Model
final_model = arima(TimeSeriesData,order = c(porder,0,qorder), method='ML')

par (mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(resid(final_model), ylab='Standardized Residuals', col="red")
abline(h=0)
acf(as.vector(resid(final_model)),main= 'ACF of the Model Residuals', col="red")
pacf(as.vector(resid(final_model)),main='PACF of the Model Residuals', col="red")
qqnorm(resid(final_model), col="red")
qqline(resid(final_model), col="red")

Response: Prediction Accuracy

For weekly CNY, the MAPE is 0.4651366 and the PM is 10.97797. We see from the plots above that all weekly data points, along with all the data, is within the 90% prediction bands.

For weekly JPY, the MAPE is 0.4512785 and the PM is 1.158028. We see from the plots above that all weekly data points, along with all the data, is within the 90% prediction bands.

In comparing the MAPE and PM for both currencies for the weekly data, we see that the MAPE is minimally higher for CNY with respect to JPY, however the PM is lower for JPY. MAPE estimates by minimizing absolute prediction errors, and since the JPY weekly value is lower than the CNY value, it suggests that the JPY is a better fit - although they are almost the same and likely no conclusions can be drawn from MAPE comparison. The closer the PM values is to zero, the better the prediction is. With a lower PM, the JPY weekly model is a better fit than that of CNY.

    modij = arima(TimeSeriesData,order = c(p[i],0,q[j]), method='ML')
    aic[i,j] = modij$aic-2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)+2*(p[i]+q[j]+1)*n/(n-p[i]-q[j]-2)

3c. Calculate Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) and Precision Measure (PM). How many observations are within the prediction bands? Compare the accuracy of the predictions for the two time series using these two measures.

out_pred = out_pred_cny_m
TimeSeriesDataTest = monthly.CNY.ts.test
#MAPE
mean(abs((TimeSeriesDataTest-out_pred$pred)/TimeSeriesDataTest)) * 100 #in percent
## [1] 0.2985237
### Precision Measure (PM)
sum((TimeSeriesDataTest - out_pred$pred)^2)/sum((TimeSeriesDataTest-mean(TimeSeriesDataTest))^2)
## [1] 7.182375
out_pred = out_pred_jpy_m
TimeSeriesDataTest = monthly.JPY.ts.test
#MAPE
mean(abs((TimeSeriesDataTest-out_pred$pred)/TimeSeriesDataTest)) * 100 #in percent

### Precision Measure (PM)
sum((TimeSeriesDataTest - out_pred$pred)^2)/sum((TimeSeriesDataTest-mean(TimeSeriesDataTest))^2)
## [1] 1.706288

Response: Predictions

For monthly CNY, the MAPE is 0.2985237 and the PM is 7.182375. We see from the plots above that both monthly data points, along with all the data, is within the 90% prediction bands.

For monthly JPY, the MAPE is 0.5475758 and the PM is 1.706288. We see from the plots above that both monthly data points, along with all the data, is within the 90% prediction bands.

In comparing the MAPE and PM for both currencies for the monthly data, we see that the MAPE is higher for JPY with respect to CNY, however the PM is lower. MAPE estimates by minimizing absolute prediction errors, and since the CNY monthly is lower than the JPY value, it suggests that the CNY is a better fit. However, the closer the PM values is to zero, the better the prediction is. With a lower PM, the JPY monthly model is a better fit than that of CNY.

Response: Prediction Comparison

In the CNY dataset, we see that the monthly predictions, which are in green, are slightly closer to the actual weekly data points when compared to the weekly predictions. Please note that i centered the data points in the middle of the month to more easily describe. In the JPY dataset, we see the we see the same, but given a wider range in the weekly values, much of the nuanced volatility is not captured. From a percentage variation, this is likely minimal, but when plotted as absolute points, it appears the weekly prediction best captures this nuance.

Question 5. Reflection on ARIMA (5 points)

Considering your understanding of the ARIMA model in general as well as what your understanding of the behavior of the currency exchange data based on the completion of the above questions, how would you personally regard the effectiveness of ARIMA modelling? Where would it be appropriate to use it for forecasting and where would you recommend against? What are some specific points of caution one would need to consider when considering using it?

Response: Reflection on ARIMA

I personally was surprised as how well ARIMA modeling fit the currency exchange data. I do think that it would be appropriate for forecasting, but only in the short term, looking at most a few weeks out. We saw that the 90% prediction bands were diverging as time went out, expecting increased volatility. I would caution on using data without considering the training period to ensure that there were no external factors, such as currency pegging or change in leadership that would naturally cause the exchange rate to become more volatile than normal. The same reasoning is that you should not look to predict into a time period where those factors exist. I do recommend extensive goodness of fit and residual analysis, as we saw that the quality of the fit can easily change depending on the order of the model and the frequency of the measurement within the training data.
